default3.8.
default3. How do we measure and report on success and failure? What does success look like?
default&#xa0;
defaultManagement needs to be lead by carefully constructed 
default‘
defaultsmart
default’
default objectives. INNS 
defaultcan be regarded as successfully managed
default when they have been prevented from invading the 
defaultUK
default through effective legislation and/or quarantine. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn some cases 
defaultinvading or established INNS may 
defaulthave been controlled successfully 
defaultbut the expected positive impacts such as evident restoration of native species and/or habitats
default or wider 
defaultsocietal or economic benefit may not have been measured. 
defaultThe f
defaultailure of management of INNS is rarely reported
default. This may be
default because objectives were poorly defined at the outset.
default&#xa0;
defaultA s
defaulttrengthened GB INNS Framework Strategy 
defaultcould help to address this problem
default, especially if
default it is
default more inclusive of NGOs in decision making
default and
default includ
defaultes
default on appropriate application of the precautionary principle.
default&#xa0;
default3.8.
default4. Should there be a
default UK/all 
defaultIreland
default approach to management of INNS?
default&#xa0;
defaultINNSs do not respect international boundaries, especially when there is no sea barrier or obvious border control. It makes sense to support the strengthening of al 
defaultUK
default/ all 
defaultIreland
default strategy to tackle INNS. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAgain a strengthened GB INNS Framework Strat
defaultegy has a supporting role here, as it does in promoting functional working links between Departments at state borders.
